    <h1><%= title %></h1>
    <p>Basic steps for kitchen composting (check hotel's specific procedures).</p>

    <div class="guide-content">
        <h2>1. Collect Organic Scraps</h2>
        <ul>
            <li>Use designated kitchen compost bins.</li>
            <li>Collect fruit/vegetable peels, cores, cuttings.</li>
            <li>Include coffee grounds, paper filters, tea bags (no staples/plastic).</li>
            <li>Include eggshells.</li>
            <li><b>Avoid:</b> Meat, dairy, bones, oils/fats, diseased plants, non-organic materials.</li>
        </ul>

         <h2>2. Transfer to Main Compost Area</h2>
        <ul>
            <li>Regularly empty kitchen bins into the hotel's main compost collection point (e.g., outdoor bin, designated pickup area).</li>
            <li>Follow procedures for securing the main bin to prevent pests.</li>
        </ul>

         <h2>3. Balancing Browns and Greens (If managing onsite bin)</h2>
         <p><i>(This section applies if the hotel manages its own compost pile/bin, otherwise skip to Step 4).</i></p>
        <ul>
            <li>Compost needs a mix of "Greens" (nitrogen-rich, like food scraps) and "Browns" (carbon-rich, like dried leaves, cardboard scraps, sawdust).</li>
            <li>Aim for roughly 2-3 parts Browns to 1 part Greens by volume.</li>
            <li>Layer materials or mix them gently.</li>
            <li>Keep the pile moist (like a damp sponge), not waterlogged.</li>
            <li>Aerate the pile occasionally (turn with a pitchfork) if managing an active bin.</li>
        </ul>

         <h2>4. Follow Hotel Pickup/Processing Schedule</h2>
         <ul>
             <li>Ensure compostable waste is ready according to the schedule provided by the hotel or waste management partner.</li>
             <li>Use designated bins/bags as instructed.</li>
         </ul>

          <h2>Key Reminders</h2>
         <ul>
             <li>Clean collection bins regularly.</li>
             <li>Always check hotel-specific guidelines.</li>
             <li>When in doubt about an item, put it in general waste.</li>
         </ul>

    </div>


